<font color="#FF0000">SOURCES</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan 28  0:09:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hey Mike:<br>
     As a educator, I had the same problem as you.  There are many sources on the Vietnam War out there, some good, some bad, but many are biased to a &quot;anti-US&quot; or &quot;anti-war&quot;<br>
stance, whether intentionally or unintentionally.  Each writer is entitled to there own point of view, but not there own facts.  I can appreciate your search for unbiased facts on the war.  In creating my lessons and discussions on Vietnam for the classes I've taught, I've used a variety of texts that each focused on a different part of the war.  I hope some of these texts may help you in your discussions.  I did a lot of research on vietnam war and as a educator have viewed many sources.  I too have have read and viewed the books you mentioned, but also sought out other smaller, more focused sources.  Here are some of my sources, though none are definitive one works:<br>
1.  The Vietnam Experience Series-The series of books from Boston Publishing and are usually the mainstay of most libraries.  They author is a Nam vet and the editor in chief worked for Johnson.  It presents a decent account of the war and a variety of view-points and stances, all credible.<br>
2.  Vietnam War Almanac-a good book by Col. Harry G. Summers,editor of Vietnam Magazine, published by Facts on File in 1985 and 1987.  It contains data on many subjects.<br>
3.  The Vietnam Order of Battle by Shelby Stanton-published by Galahad Books.  A massive source on military commitment.  The books lists in detail and describes every Army, Navy, Air Force, Marine, New Zealand, Australian, and Korean unit that served in Vietnam during the entire war.  It also has a impressive section on US casualty data, giving totals on all branches, but especially categorizing Army hostile and non-hostile deaths.  For example, did you know that 17 Army guys died of hepatitus and 680 from accidental self destruction.  The book also has stats and photos on all weapons used and a whole section on a operational chronology listing and describing all campaigns.  A nice reference!<br>
4.  Another source which has helped me much is the March 1993 issue of Veterans of Foreign Wars magazine.  If you can get it Mike, it has a accurate statistical data and a impressive detailed Chronology on the war.  I believe lecturers and educators may obtain copies of the Chronolgy from the VFW.<br>
5.  A excellent source on our enemy, the VC/NVA, which I have drew from for lessons is Inside the VC and NVA, by Michael Lee Lanning and Dan Cragg.  Written by two Nam vets, it uses interviews and data to explore every aspect of the NVA and VC armies in Vietnam.  It is a informative and surprising source on the other side.<br>
For curriculum and research use, I have compiled other sources, many on specific areas of the conflict and aftermath, such as personal accounts and research jounal data.  I would be happy to share them with you.  Post a note on what you need and I can share them with you.  To the rest of the guys reading this post, what sources have you encountered that  you considered decent.  Mike and especially myself would like to hear about them. <br>

